[1
Date: 25 Feb 2001
From: The Pig Disease Information Centre <pdic@btinternet.com>
******
Source: BBC Radio News
The 7th outbreak of Foot and Mouth Disease (FMD) has been confirmed in
500 cattle and 1500 sheep on farm in Highampton, North Devon. The
premises have been exporting livestock to Europe (prior to the ban last
week) particularly France.
The company owns 12 other farms in Cornwall and Devon and also has
contacts in the North of England. There is no known link to other
confirmed outbreaks.
The first sign was a mouth ulcer in a cow, but 50 other cattle are now
showing early symptoms. FMD is difficult to diagnose in sheep.
******
Source: UK pig producers discussion forum, 25 Feb 2001 [edited
5/2/2001. Andrew Leeder.
Vaccination is a complex subject and there are pros and cons, but almost
everything you could possibly want to know about the "Strategy for
Emergency Vaccination against FMD" is in the EU Scientific Committee
document:
<http://europa.eu.int/comm/food/fs/sc/scah/out22_en.html>
The EU sees this generally as supporting slaughtering, not a substitute,
and there are trade issues too, particularly if international authorities
have not been keeping up to date with modern methods which help
distinguish between vaccinated and infected animals. The UK holds stocks
of EU vaccine and MAFF says on their website they will do the vaccination
free of charge if it is decided to be beneficial. The EU report says
"farmers whose herds/flocks are vaccinated and who suffer losses as a
result of the restrictions placed on them should be fully compensated"
Other News updates and FMD overview at:< http://www.pighealth.com>
